body:
I tried this code:

```rust
fn main() {}

fn f1() {
    let mut a = 1;
    let b = &mut a;
    let foo = |i: &mut i32| {};
    foo(b);
    foo(b);
}

fn f2() {
    let mut a = 1;
    let b = &mut a;
    let foo = |i| {};
    foo(&mut *b);
    foo(&mut *b); // error! But I think it should be compiled successfully
}
```

I expected to see this happen:
```
    Finished dev [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.69s
     Running `target\debug\nobug.exe`
```

I modify it to:
```rust
fn main() {}

fn f1() {
    let mut a = 1;
    let b = &mut a;
    let foo = |i: &mut i32| {};
    foo(b);
}

fn f2() {
    let mut a = 1;
    let b = &mut a;
    let foo = |i| {};
    foo(&mut *b);
}
```
Then I type `rustc --emit=mir .\src\main.rs` to generates `main.mir` and found that mir of `f1` and `f2` are exactly the same. The `foo(b);` in `f1` and `foo(&mut *b);` in `f2` both pass the reborrow of `b` into the function. However, the previous code failed to compile.😢

Instead, this happened:
```
error[E0499]: cannot borrow `*b` as mutable more than once at a time
  --> src\main.rs:16:9
   |
15 |     foo(&mut *b);
   |         ------- first mutable borrow occurs here
16 |     foo(&mut *b);
   |     --- ^^^^^^^ second mutable borrow occurs here
   |     |
   |     first borrow later used by call

error: aborting due to previous error; 2 warnings emitted

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0499`.
error: could not compile `learn`.
```

